1- HISTORY OF LIGHT\b0\par
\par
In ancient civilizations, light had deep meanings both as a physical phenomenon and as a metaphysical concept. Ancient Greek, Egyptian and Islamic scholars developed different perspectives on the nature of light, and these understandings eventually formed the cornerstones of science and philosophy.\par
In ancient Greece, light was considered an important subject of natural philosophy. Thoughts on the nature of light were shaped especially by philosophers such as Pythagoras, Plato, and Aristotle. Pythagoras and his followers suggested that we perceive the world through the rays of light coming out of the eye. According to this view, the light coming out of our eyes interacts with objects and enables our ability to see. Empedocles accepted light as one of the four basic elements that exist in the universe. According to him, there was a kind of internal light source inside the eye, and this combined with the light outside provided vision. Plato used light as a symbol of truth and knowledge with his \ldblquote Allegory of the Cave\rdblquote . He believed that light was an element that illuminated objects in the material world, as well as enlightening the soul and mind of man, enabling us to reach the truth. According to him, light was not just a physical event, but a symbol of knowledge and divine reality. Aristotle examined the nature of light on a more scientific level and suggested that vision occurred when light reflected from objects to our eyes. He argued that light did not have a material structure, but interacted with objects. In Egyptian civilization, light was of great importance both religiously and cosmologically. Light was generally seen as a power associated with divinity. The most powerful symbol of light in ancient Egypt was the Sun God Ra. Ra was worshiped as both a creative power and the source of light. The birth of the sun was seen as the daily re-creation of the universe, and this creation was realized thanks to light. In Egypt, light was a symbol of life, order, and the eternal cycle. According to Egyptian cosmology, light won a victory over darkness at the beginning of creation. While darkness symbolized chaos and the absence of order, light represented order, consciousness, and life. \par
In Egyptian art, light was shown as a force separating gods from humans. Pharaohs were often associated with gods and depicted surrounded by light, symbolizing their divine origins. In Islamic civilization, light has been studied in depth with its scientific, philosophical, and mystical meanings. Both the concept of NUR in the Quran and the scientific studies of Islamic scholars have addressed various aspects of light. Ibn al-Haytham (Alhazen) is one of the most important names in the Islamic world who has done scientific studies on light. His works on optics have revolutionized the scientific study of the nature of light. Ibn al-Haytham experimentally proved that light does not come from the eye, but from objects and is reflected in our eyes. In his work Kitab al-Menazir, he examined optical phenomena such as the refraction and reflection of light in depth. Ibn Sina, one of the greatest names in Islamic philosophy, examined the relationship between light and matter in depth and saw light as a bridge between the physical and metaphysical worlds. According to him, light both makes objects visible in the physical sense and provides the illumination of the truth in the spiritual sense.\par
The expression \ldblquote Allah is the light of the heavens and the earth\rdblquote  in the Quran has given a deep metaphysical meaning to the concept of light in Islamic philosophy. Light has become the symbol of divine wisdom and enlightenment. In Sufi thought, light is an element that illuminates the heart of man and makes the presence of Allah felt everywhere. Here, light has been seen as a symbol of knowledge and spiritual enlightenment. In Islamic civilization, light is a symbol that carries deep meanings, especially in the philosophy of Sufism and mystical thought. The great names of Sufism, Muhyiddin Ibn Arabi, Abdulkadir Geylani, Mevlana and other Islamic mystics, have considered light as a reflection of both spiritual enlightenment and divine truths. In this context, light has an important place in the thoughts of Islamic mystics both metaphorically and existentially.\par
Muhyiddin Arabi, as one of the greatest theorists of Sufism, has given a deep metaphysical meaning to the concept of light. In his understanding of "Vahdet-i Vuj" (unity of existence), light is considered a manifestation of the divine existence and the reality of everything. According to him, the essence of Allah is light (nur) and this light manifests itself in the creation of the universe and at every level of existence. Allah is the essence of everything and His light encompasses the universe. Every being created by Allah is a reflection of His light. This idea explains how the divine reality manifests itself on all beings in the works of Muhyiddin Arabi. Muhyiddin Arabi attributes a deep meaning to the Surah Nur in the Quran.\par
The expression "Allah is the light of the heavens and the earth" in this surah indicates that His existence in both the physical and metaphysical worlds is a reality that encompasses everything like light. According to Muhyiddin Arabi, the human soul can be illuminated by the light of Allah, and this illumination strengthens the metaphysical connection of man with Allah. This is at the center of a spiritual journey and is called "marifat" (reaching the truth). When a person is illuminated by the divine light, he can grasp true knowledge and the truth of Allah. Abdulkadir Geylani is one of the important names of Islamic Sufism, and in his teachings, light is seen as spiritual illumination and a reflection of the divine presence. Geylani describes the light of Allah as a force that illuminates hearts and souls. According to him, a person cannot reach true knowledge unless their heart is cleansed and illuminated by the light of Allah. \par
This process of illumination begins with a person turning to Allah with the purity and sincerity of their worldly life. According to Geylani, when the heart is filled with the light of God, all of a person\rquote s internal and external perceptions are illuminated and they reach the light of truth. Geylani says that knowing oneself, that is, understanding one\rquote s inner truth, is possible with the light of God. The true existence of a person is a reflection of the light of God, and a person illuminated by this light can grasp both God\rquote s truth and his own truth. Mevlana Celaleddin Rumi frequently used the metaphor of light in the context of love, truth, and divine wisdom. In Mevlana\rquote s works, light is seen as an element that guides a person on their spiritual journey. According to Mevlana, the light of God is the highest manifestation of love. Love acts as a light that leads a person to God. According to him, love illuminates a person\rquote s soul, and this illumination is one of the most important tools in reaching God\rquote s truth. \par
He frequently deals with this subject in his work \ldblquote Mesnevi\rdblquote : \ldblquote Be like the sun, illuminating everything.\rdblquote  The expression explains how Mevlana integrated with the transcendent divine light. Mevlana explains man's inability to see the truth in the world as a curtain drawn in front of his eyes. This curtain is man's heedlessness, ambitions and ego. However, the light of Allah tears this curtain and opens man's eyes to the truth. According to Mevlana, this is the basis of spiritual awakening. Mevlana often describes the world as a shadow and the truth as light. He says that this world is temporary and misleading, and that true enlightenment is found in the light of Allah. Unless a person is enlightened by this light, he cannot fully comprehend the world and himself. In the thought of Hac\f2\u305? Bekta\'ba Veli, light is seen as a divine element that illuminates the essence of man. Enlightenment and purification are possible with the light of Allah. Suhrawardi's "I\'barak Philosophy" (Philosophy of Enlightenment) is a system of thought based directly on the understanding of light. According to him, light is the basis of existence and the essence of everything is light. Light determines the degrees of beings; The purest light is the light of God, and other beings exist by sharing in this light. In Yunus Emre's poems, light is a symbol of love for God and spiritual consciousness. The light of God fills the heart of man, illuminating him and leading him to the truth. \par
Theories on the nature of light have tried to shed light on one of the most fundamental questions in scientific history. The answers to these questions have focused on issues such as what light is, how it moves, and how it interacts with matter. Many scientists, from Isaac Newton to James Clerk Maxwell, have made important contributions to understanding the nature of light and laid the foundations for our understanding of modern physics. Isaac Newton had a great impact on the scientific world of the period with the theories he developed on the nature of light in the 17th century. Newton suggested that light is basically composed of particles. This view is detailed in his works on optics. According to Newton, light is a flow of very small material particles, and these particles move in a linear path. Newton showed that white light can be separated into different colors with his prism experiments. These experiments were findings that were thought to support the particle structure of light. Newton attributed this dispersion of light to the refraction of particles at different speeds. Newton's particle theory was quite successful in explaining the reflection and refraction of light. According to him, when light particles hit surfaces, reflection occurs, while in some cases, particles pass the boundary between mediums and refraction occurs. Newton's theory on the particle structure of light was widely accepted and remained the dominant view in the scientific world for many years. However, this theory had difficulty fully explaining some properties of light. In particular, events such as interference and diffraction were incompatible with the particle theory.\par
Christiaan Huygens developed an alternative theory about the nature of light at the same time as Newton. According to this view, known as the wave theory, light moved as a wave, not a particle. Huygens proposed that every point of light could be considered a wave source and that these waves propagated in all directions. According to him, every point on a surface produced new waves and that the light wave was propagated by the combination of these waves. Huygens' wave theory successfully explained the interference and diffraction phenomena that Newton's particle theory had difficulty explaining. In particular, the diffraction pattern that emerged when light passed through thin gaps was compatible with the wave theory. However, Huygens' wave theory also had shortcomings. In particular, the idea that waves must propagate in a medium was inadequate in explaining how light moved in a vacuum. For this reason, the wave theory was not as accepted as Newton's particle theory. Towards the end of the century, Thomas Young and Augustin-Jean Fresnel made important contributions to the wave theory. Young's famous double-slit experiment in 1801 definitively confirmed the wave nature of light. Young passed a beam of light through two narrow slits and observed an interference pattern forming in the background. If light were a particle, such a pattern would not be possible. This experiment was accepted as evidence of the wave nature of light. Fresnel expanded on Young's work and developed theories on the polarization and diffraction of light. Fresnel's work strengthened the mathematical foundations of the wave theory and suggested that light was a transverse wave. In the middle of the century, James Clerk Maxwell developed a theory that would put an end to the debates on the nature of light. Maxwell proposed that electricity and magnetism were related and that light was an electromagnetic wave. Maxwell showed that light was a fluctuation of an electromagnetic field and that these waves could propagate even in a vacuum. This solved the problem of Huygens' wave theory of propagation in a vacuum. \par
Light was now considered a wave that did not require a medium. Maxwell developed a set of equations that unified electricity and magnetism. These equations showed that light was an electromagnetic wave and that it traveled at a certain speed (the speed of light). Maxwell\rquote s equations explained that light was carried by both electric and magnetic fields. Maxwell\rquote s theory suggested that the speed of light was a universal constant and that this speed depended only on the electrical and magnetic constants. This showed that the speed of light was inherently constant and would not change in any medium. The theories developed on the nature of light from Newton to Maxwell played a critical role in clarifying one of the most important questions in modern physics. While Newton\rquote s particle theory viewed light as material particles, the work of Huygens and Maxwell revealed that light was a wave and associated with electromagnetic fields. These theories helped explain both the wave and particle properties of light and formed the basis of our current understanding of quantum physics. Quantum physics, a field that revolutionized the understanding of the nature of light, explains the behavior of light as both a particle and a wave. These two natures are defined by a concept called "wave-particle duality" and is one of the fundamental principles of modern physics. Wave-particle duality states that light and other quantum objects can exhibit both wave and particle properties depending on their state. This duality goes beyond the rules of classical physics and is one of the fundamental principles of quantum mechanics. Light is thought of as elementary particles called photons. Photons are massless and move as electromagnetic waves. The particle properties of light emerge in the following cases:\par
Photoelectric Effect: Albert Einstein discovered in 1905 that light affects matter through photons, which are packets of energy. This effect is observed when light hits a surface and releases electrons. This event is considered evidence of the particle properties of light. On the other hand; the energy of photons is related to its frequency. This relationship, expressed by Planck's formula (E = hf), shows that each photon has a certain energy. Here E is energy, h is Planck's constant and f is frequency. The wave properties of light are particularly evident in two important experiments: Thomas Young's 1801 experiment showed that light passing through a pair of slits produced an interference pattern. This pattern is evidence of light's behavior as a wave. Its wave nature is demonstrated by the maximum and minimum light intensities produced by the interference of the waves emerging from the slits.\par
In Diffraction and Polarization; when light passes through thin gaps or edges, it diffracts; this is another example of wave nature. Also, the polarization of light is a reflection of wave properties; light waves move by vibrating in a certain plane.\par
Quantum mechanics uses the concept of "wave function" to explain wave-particle duality. Wave function is a mathematical function that describes the state of a particle and expresses the properties of the particle such as its position and momentum with a certain probability distribution.\par
In Born Rule; squaring the wave function gives the probability of a particle being in a certain position. In other words, the magnitude of the wave function expresses the probability of the particle.\par
When a measurement is made in quantum mechanics, the wave function collapses and takes a certain state. This leads to the particle having a definite position. This situation shows the transition between wave and particle nature.\par
Quantum field theory (QFT) deepens wave-particle duality even further. According to this theory, particles are considered as excitations of fields. For example, the quantum state of the electromagnetic field represents photons. This perspective helps to understand light and other elementary particles in a more comprehensive framework.\par
The wave-particle duality of light is one of the fundamental features of quantum physics and is a rich field from both theoretical and experimental perspectives. This duality has pushed the boundaries of modern science and deepened our understanding of the nature of light. Quantum mechanics provides the mathematical framework necessary to understand this complex situation, while experiments have revealed both particle and wave properties of light. This issue continues to be a subject of research and discussion.\par
The discovery of the photon is an important turning point in quantum mechanics and the nature of light. While the photon is defined as the elementary particle of light, quantum mechanics helps us to understand the wave-particle duality of light. The term photon was introduced by Albert Einstein in 1905. Einstein proposed that light can behave like a particle and that these particles can be thought of as specific energy packets (photons). Einstein proved the existence of photons with his studies on the photoelectric effect. When light hits a surface, photons with a certain energy can release electrons on the surface. This event shows that light behaves as energy packets. Einstein's concept of photons is based on the quantum theory developed by Max Planck in 1900. Planck discovered that energy levels have certain quantal values \u8203?\u8203?in his studies on heat radiation. Einstein developed the concept of photons by applying these findings to light. Quantum mechanics plays a critical role in understanding the nature of light. Light is studied as a quantum object that exhibits both wave and particle properties. Quantum mechanics accepts that the wave and particle properties of light complement each other. Photons behave like waves under certain conditions and like particles under other conditions. \par
This duality is one of the fundamental principles of quantum mechanics. In quantum mechanics, the state of light is represented by the wave function. This function gives the probability of a photon being in a certain position or state. When a measurement is made, the wave function collapses to a definite state. Quantum field theory describes photons as quantum states of the electromagnetic field. In this framework, photons are excitations of the field, and light is explained by the dynamics of this field. QFT provides a comprehensive framework for understanding the interactions of light and other elementary particles. Photons are of critical importance in many areas of quantum mechanics and modern physics: Photons play a fundamental role in quantum communication and computation. Applications such as quantum cryptography rely on the manipulation of the quantum states of photons. Photons are an important research topic in the field of quantum optics. The quantum states of light are used in the development of new optical technologies. Photons are fundamental components that carry information from the early universe to the present day. Light plays a critical role in astronomical observations and in the study of cosmic events.\par
