\b 2- THE SCIENTIFIC DIMENSION OF LIGHT AND PHOTONS\b0\par
\par
Photons are fundamental particles that exhibit unique behaviors in the quantum world. Within the framework of quantum mechanics, the properties of photons such as superposition and quantum entanglement constitute the most interesting and impressive aspects of modern physics. Photons are considered quantum objects that exhibit both wave and particle properties. These properties have been observed in various experiments: Photons can behave like waves in one experiment and like particles in another. This shows that the two natures of light complement each other. Thomas Young's famous double-slit experiment clearly demonstrated the wave nature of photons. When a photon passes through two slits, it creates a pattern by the interference of the waves. However, even when photons are sent individually, they create the same pattern over time. This shows that photons interact with each other while in superposition.\par
Superposition refers to the ability of a quantum system to be in more than one state at the same time. Photons can have more than one possibility at the same time thanks to this feature. A photon can have the probability of being in a certain state (for example, in a certain polarization direction). However, it also has the probability of being in different polarization directions. This state indicates that the photon is in a superposition state. Measuring the superposition state of a photon causes the photon to collapse into a certain state. In other words, the photon in the superposition state chooses a certain state when the measurement is made. This process is one of the fundamental features of quantum mechanics. \par
Quantum entanglement refers to a state in which two or more quantum systems are interconnected and a change in the state of one instantly affects the state of the other. Photons are one of the most well-known examples of this phenomenon. When two photons interact in such a way as to create an entangled state, these photons become entangled with each other. In an entangled state, when the polarization or other property of one photon is measured, the state of the other photon is determined instantly, regardless of the independent distance. The existence of quantum entanglement has been tested by theories developed by John Bell. Bell's theorem shows that entangled systems cannot be explained by classical physics. Experiments have proven that entangled photons have a relationship beyond classical theories.\par
Photons are elementary particles that behave with interesting properties such as superposition and entanglement in the quantum world. These properties form the cornerstones of modern physics and technology. While quantum mechanics helps us understand these properties, the behavior of photons constitutes an important area that will guide future research and applications. The place of photons in the quantum world deepens our physical understanding while also opening the doors to new technologies.\par
The electromagnetic spectrum is a wide range where electromagnetic waves with different wavelengths and frequencies come together. This spectrum extends from a wide range of radio waves, including visible light, to gamma rays. Here are the main sections of the electromagnetic spectrum:\par
1. Radio Waves: They have the longest wavelengths (from about 1 mm to several kilometers). Frequency: Varies between 3 Hz and 300 GHz.\par
Usage Areas: Radio and television broadcasts, mobile phone communication, wireless internet and radar systems.\par
2. Microwaves: Wavelength: Varies between 1 mm and 1 m. Frequency: Between 300 MHz and 300 GHz.\par
Usage Areas: Microwave ovens, satellite communication, wireless communication and radar systems.\par
3. Infrared (IR) Light: Wavelength: Between 700 nm and 1 mm. Frequency: Between 300 GHz and 430 THz.\par
Usage Areas: Heat detection, night vision systems, remote controls and thermal imaging.\par
4. Visible Light: Wavelength: Between 400 nm and 700 nm. Frequency: Between 430 THz and 750 THz.\par
Usage Areas: Light spectrum that the human eye can perceive. Colors vary by wavelength (for example, blue light has shorter wavelengths, red light has longer wavelengths).\par
5. Ultraviolet (UV) Light: Wavelength: 10 nm to 400 nm. Frequency: 750 THz to 30 PHz.\par
Uses: Sterilization, UV lamps, sunlight, melanin production in the skin. Also, some types can cause DNA damage.\par
6. X-Rays: Wavelength: 0.01 nm to 10 nm. Frequency: 30 PHz to 30 EHz.\par
Uses: Medical imaging (x-ray), industrial inspection, and some scientific research.\par
7. Gamma Rays: Wavelength: Shorter than 0.001 nm. Frequency: Higher than 30 EHz.\par
Areas of Use: Nuclear medicine (cancer treatment), radiation therapy, space research and some scientific experiments. All electromagnetic waves travel at the speed of light in a vacuum, which is approximately 299,792 km/s. As the wavelength decreases (frequency increases), the energy of the waves increases. Gamma rays have the highest energy, while radio waves have the lowest energy. The nature of light has been studied in depth within the framework of quantum electrodynamics (QED). QED is the quantum field theory that explains electromagnetic interactions, and one of the most important contributions in this field was made by Richard Feynman. Quantum Electrodynamics (QED) is a theory that combines light and electromagnetic fields with quantum mechanics. This theory explains the interactions of photons and electrically charged particles (e.g. electrons). QED defines photons as quantum states of the electromagnetic field. While electrons interact with photons and exert forces, the rules of these interactions are determined by QED. QED is a fundamental quantum field theory and includes concepts related to the quantum state of fields. In this context, particles are considered as excitations of the field. Photons are waves of this field. Richard Feynman made many important contributions to QED. \par
Feynman developed Feynman diagrams, which visually represent the interactions of particles. These diagrams are a powerful tool for understanding how interactions occur. The diagrams visualize time, energy, and the paths of particles. Feynman developed an approach in quantum field theory that allowed calculations to be done in a more systematic and understandable way. This facilitated the analysis of complex interactions. Feynman emphasized that when describing the transition of a particle from one location to another, all possible paths of this transition must be considered. This idea is a fundamental principle of quantum mechanics. QED provides a better understanding of the nature of light. To explain the relationship between the wave and particle properties of light, QED considers the situations in which light can behave as a particle and also its propagation properties as a wave. QED proposes that light exhibits both wave and particle properties. In one experiment, light may propagate as a wave, while in another experiment it may behave as a particle (photon). QED explains how electromagnetic interactions occur at the quantum level. Photons mediate the force between electrons. Electrons interact with each other by exchanging photons. QED is one of the cornerstones of modern physics and plays an important role in many applications: QED is used in areas such as laser technology and optical communication systems. Feynman diagrams are an important tool in the analysis of particle physics experiments. Fields such as quantum computers and quantum cryptography benefit from the principles of QED. Quantum electrodynamics plays a key role in understanding the nature of light, and Richard Feynman\rquote s contributions were decisive in the development of this theory. \par
QED explains the dynamics of electromagnetic interactions at the quantum level, providing a critical foundation for many areas of modern physics. Feynman\rquote s diagrams and methods help us better understand and analyze physical phenomena. The speed of light is one of the most fundamental concepts of the physical world and has a deep relationship with Albert Einstein\rquote s theory of relativity. The speed of light is considered to be approximately 299,792 km/s (about 300,000 km/s) in a vacuum, which is considered the highest speed in the universe. The speed of light is considered a constant speed in nature, and this speed has an important place, especially in the framework of the theory of relativity. It has been proven by various experiments (for example, the Michelson-Morley experiments) that the speed of light is constant. Einstein\rquote s theory of relativity consists of two main parts. Special Relativity (The theory of special relativity suggests that the speed of light is constant for every observer. This means that even if the observers are moving at different speeds, the speed of light will be measured as 299.792 km/s. The constant speed of light creates an understanding that time and space are interconnected, and the effects of relativity on time periods and lengths emerge. Time moves more slowly for a fast-moving observer than for a stationary observer. 'Time dilation'). General Relativity (General relativity explains that mass changes the path of light by curving space-time. This causes light to bend around massive objects. Gravity does not affect the speed of light, but it does change the trajectory of light. For example, the gravitational field of the Sun causes starlight to bend around the Sun. This phenomenon was observed during the 1919 solar eclipse.)\par
The speed of light means that no information or matter in the universe can move faster than this speed. This is a result of physical laws. In the framework of special relativity, how time changes as an object approaches the speed of light opens up the concept of time travel. However, in practice, reaching these speeds is not possible with current technology. The speed of light has a deep connection with the theory of relativity, and these theories play a fundamental role in our understanding of the physical universe. The constant speed of light has redefined the relationship between time and space, gravity, and motion in the universe. These concepts have allowed for important applications and understandings in many areas of modern physics.\par
