\b 4-THE COSMIC DIMENSION OF LIGHT\b0\par
\par
The formation of light in the universe since the Big Bang has a profound importance in terms of cosmology and physics. Here are the main stages in this process:\par
The birth of the universe took place approximately 13.8 billion years ago with the Big Bang. This was an extremely dense and hot state where all space, time, matter and energy came together. In the first moments of the Big Bang, the universe was in a hot and dense plasma state. At this stage, elementary particles such as atoms, protons and neutrons began to form. However, due to the high temperature, it was not possible for atoms to come together. In the first few minutes, protons and neutrons combined to form helium and other light elements. This process is called nucleosynthesis. During the first few hundred thousand years, the temperature of the universe dropped to 3000 K. At this point, the universe became more transparent as the atoms combined. Photons began to move freely without interacting with the atoms. Formation of the Light Source: After about 400,000 years, the universe cooled sufficiently to form atoms. This provided an environment in which photons could move freely. This process is known as "Hawking radiation". During this period of the universe, light first became free and radiation known as "cosmic microwave background radiation" emerged. This is considered a remnant of the Big Bang and was the first stage of the formation of light in the universe. \par
After about 1 billion years, the universe cooled, allowing the formation of galaxies and stars. Gas clouds collapsed under the influence of gravity, allowing the formation of stars and galaxies. The first stars emerged from the condensation of gas clouds consisting of hydrogen and helium. These stars produced heavier elements through nucleosynthesis processes, producing more light in the universe. During the life cycles of stars, heavy elements are released into space through supernova explosions. These elements are used in the formation of new stars and planets. This process reinforces the role of light spreading and cosmic radiation in the universe. Today, different wavelengths of light are observed in various regions of the universe. Different wavelengths such as visible light, ultraviolet light, infrared light and radio waves carry the traces of physical events occurring in the universe.\par
The formation of light in the universe since the Big Bang is a complex process that extends from the first moments to the formation of galaxies and stars. This process is shaped by both physical laws and cosmic events, and helps us understand the dynamic nature of the universe and the importance of light. Light is a fundamental part of the history and evolutionary process of the universe and offers scientists the key to unraveling cosmic mysteries.\par
Black holes are known as the densest and most mysterious structures in the universe. The fact that light cannot escape from black holes is one of the basic characteristics of these celestial bodies. Black holes are usually formed as a result of the collapse of massive stars in supernova explosions at the end of their life cycles. The gravitational force of the star overcomes the internal pressure and causes the star to collapse to its center. Stephen Hawking suggested that black holes can emit radiation in the vacuum of space. However, this radiation cannot escape the gravitational field of a black hole, so black holes are actually called "black". There is a certain boundary around a black hole, called the "event horizon". The event horizon is the point in the gravitational field of a black hole beyond which nothing, including light, can escape. Once light passes the event horizon, it is trapped by the gravitational force of the black hole. Although the speed of light is the fastest in the universe, the gravitational force of the black hole is so intense that not even light can escape its pull.\par
Albert Einstein\rquote s theory of general relativity is a critical foundation for explaining the existence of black holes. According to the theory, massive objects affect the surrounding space by curving spacetime. Black holes are at the extreme ends of this curve. The event horizon can be thought of as a kind of \ldblquote closing\rdblquote  of spacetime. When an observer observes an object approaching the event horizon, they notice that time slows down, a result of light not being able to escape from the black hole. Black holes can pull in the matter around them to form disks. As this matter heats up and spins, it emits intense light. This light causes a structure that looks like a \ldblquote halo\rdblquote  to form around the black hole. Black holes cause light to bend, distorting images of objects in the background. This phenomenon occurs when light is affected by the gravitational field of the black hole. Black holes cannot be observed directly, but the effects on their surroundings can be studied using electromagnetic radiation such as X-rays and radio waves. For example, X-ray emission from the disk of matter surrounding a black hole provides information about the existence of a black hole. In 2019, the image of the supermassive black hole at the center of the M87 galaxy was obtained with observations made by the Event Horizon Telescope. This further confirmed the existence of black holes. The relationships between dark energy, dark matter, and light are one of the most interesting and complex topics in modern cosmology. \par
Dark matter is a type of matter found in the universe but cannot be observed directly and does not interact with light. Its existence is assumed to understand the gravitational effects of galaxies and galaxy clusters. Dark matter is invisible because it does not interact directly with light. However, it can be observed indirectly through phenomena such as the rotation speeds of galaxies and gravitational lensing. The bending of light by dark matter helps us understand this matter indirectly. Dark energy is a type of energy proposed to explain the accelerating expansion of the universe. This energy makes up about 70% of the universe and accelerates the expansion by reversing gravitational attraction. Dark energy does not affect the path of light, but the expansion of the universe can change the wavelengths of light. This effect is known as cosmic redshift. Light from distant galaxies is stretched in wavelength due to the expansion of the universe, causing visible light to be redshifted.\par
Dark matter and dark energy play an important role in the dynamic balance of the universe. While dark matter enables the formation of galaxies and their large structures, dark energy accelerates the expansion of the universe. These two have complementary effects on the evolution and structure of the universe. Under certain conditions, the interactions between dark matter and dark energy are studied in simulations to understand how the structure of the universe evolves. These simulations reveal the effects of both elements on the formation of galaxies and cosmic structure.\par
Light is the main tool for studying the structures of matter in the universe (galaxies, galaxy clusters). Dark matter and dark energy affect these structures and determine the distribution of light in the universe. Light indirectly provides information about dark matter and dark energy. This radiation left over from the Big Bang provides information about the early universe. Its interaction with dark matter and dark energy helps us understand the dynamics of the early universe.\par
