 Quantum superposition means that matter is not in a certain state, but will change to a state under the influence of the observer. In other words, while classical physics says that matter is fixed and definite, quantum physics argues that matter is in uncertainty as long as it is not observed. This new perspective shows that matter exists only depending on the observer and does not have a certain reality when there is no observer. In other words, in the quantum world, matter has ceased to be a fixed entity, and has become a structure that is constantly changing and uncertain in interaction with the observer. At the subatomic level, that is, at the quantum level, the validity of the rules of classical physics is largely lost. Although classical physics defines matter as "hard" and "independent of space", quantum physics shows that this understanding is not correct in the subatomic world. The majority of the atom consists of "empty space" according to the classical view. However, quantum physics shows that this space is actually filled with energy, meaning that nothing is truly empty. Even the "space" between atoms is constantly filled with waves of energy. According to quantum field theory, subatomic particles are constantly in a sea of \u8203?\u8203?energy, and this energy can instantly transform into matter. \par
