\b 17- AN EVALUATION ON CONSCIOUSNESS AND AWARENESS UNDERLYING THE FOUNDATION OF REALITY\b0\par
\par
Idealistic monism is a philosophical view that argues that the mind or consciousness lies at the basis of reality. According to this view, the material world derives from consciousness or is inseparably linked to consciousness. Although some interpretations of quantum physics present concepts that are close to the arguments of idealistic monism, it is difficult to say that there is a definitive harmony between quantum physics and idealistic monism. However, some interpretations of quantum physics seem to support the philosophical principles of idealistic monism. In particular, concepts such as the Copenhagen Interpretation of quantum mechanics and the Observer Effect open up discussions about the role that consciousness plays in the formation of reality. The Copenhagen Interpretation argues that quantum systems do not have a specific state until they are observed and that observation itself determines reality. This is a parallel way of thinking to the idealistic monism view that "consciousness creates reality." However, this interpretation suggests that reality is not only the product of consciousness, but that there is a deep interaction between observation and reality.\par
Other quantum interpretations, such as the Many Worlds Interpretation and Bohm's Hidden Variable Theory, distance themselves from idealistic monism by arguing that there is a reality independent of consciousness. The Many Worlds Interpretation argues that the universe splits into multiple parallel realities as a result of each measurement, which contradicts the idea that consciousness alone shapes reality. Bohm's interpretation, on the other hand, argues that quantum systems are governed by predetermined hidden variables, which explains the relationship between consciousness and reality from a more mechanical perspective. However, theories about quantum consciousness, such as Orchestrated Objective Reduction (Orch-OR) Theory, discuss how quantum processes can affect conscious experience, and these theories may have some parallels with the idea that consciousness is the fundamental element of reality. However, these theories do not provide definitive scientific findings that confirm idealistic monism; they only open a door to philosophical interest.\par
In conclusion, it would not be correct to say that quantum physics directly confirms all elements of idealistic monism. Although quantum physics provides interpretations that can philosophically support some of the claims of idealistic monism, the nature of the quantum world and the role of consciousness in this nature are still controversial and widely discussed. Therefore, while quantum physics supports certain aspects of idealistic monism, it may deepen some paradoxes rather than resolve them.\par
