\b 32- FORMATION OF PHYSICAL BEINGS BY LIGHT, THE FUNDAMENTAL BUILDING BLOCK OF CREATION\b0\par
\par
Light plays a central role in understanding both physical beings and the universal order. In physics, light is a form of electromagnetic radiation and is carried by photons, which have both wave and particle properties. In Islamic and Sufi thought, light (nur) is considered a symbol of divine knowledge, existence and creation. The intersection of these two different perspectives is that light plays an important constructive role in both the physical universe and the metaphysical world.\par
In the physical world, light has a great effect on how beings are shaped and appear. For example, all objects we see with the eye become visible to us by reflecting the light falling on them. Light interacts with matter as an electromagnetic wave and affects the energy levels of atoms. Electrons in the structure of matter can rise to higher energy levels by absorbing photons or return to their previous levels by releasing this energy. These basic processes determine the structure and appearance of matter in the physical world. Since light also carries energy, it plays a role as a catalyst in the formation of matter and various chemical reactions. However, on a deeper level, the question of whether light is the fundamental building block of creation has both a scientific and metaphysical dimension. According to the Big Bang theory, the universe initially emerged with a dense and hot explosion of energy, and this energy transformed into mass, that is, matter. In this process, light was one of the earliest elements to form, and with the expansion of the universe, it paved the way for the formation of beings. In terms of quantum mechanics, light (photons) is considered one of the fundamental particles that carry the electromagnetic force. From this perspective, light is one of the fundamental building blocks of the universe and provides the relationship between energy and matter.\par
From a metaphysical and religious perspective, light is the essence of creation. In Islam, there is a belief that "light", which is accepted as the first creation of Allah, is the source of all beings. Allah's name "Light" expresses His aspect that illuminates everything, creates everything and is the source of knowledge. In this context, light is not only a physical phenomenon, but also a symbol of divine knowledge and existence. As a reflection of creation, light enables the formation of beings on both the physical and spiritual planes. As a result, light is a fundamental energy source that determines the visibility and structure of beings in the physical universe. In the quantum world, photons shape the interactions between substances and carry the electromagnetic force. In a metaphysical sense, light is seen as a reflection of divine existence and a symbol of creation. In both respects, light can be considered one of the basic building blocks of the formation of beings and creation.\par
\par
\b 33- DIVINE ORDER AND THE CONSTANT SPEED OF LIGHT\b0\par
\par
The speed of light is one of the fundamental constants of the universe, and understanding why this speed is the same for everything is one of the most fundamental questions of physics. Light is propagated by photons, which travel as electromagnetic waves, and since these photons have no mass, they travel at their highest speed in the vacuum of space. The speed of light in a vacuum is approximately 299,792,458 meters per second (approximately 300,000 km/s). This speed is at the center of Einstein's general and special theories of relativity and is a fundamental limit for all observations and events in the universe. So why does light exceed everything in the universe at the same speed, and can this be seen as an indication of a divine order?\par
The fact that light travels at a constant speed is a direct result of the symmetry and order in the structure of the universe. Physical laws operate in the same way everywhere in the universe, and this symmetry ensures that the speed of light is universal. According to Einstein's theory of special relativity, no object or information can exceed the speed of light. This speed is considered a constant in the structure of the universe. The invariance of the speed of light also deeply affects our perception of time and space; moving observers may be in different time zones, but the speed of light remains the same for both. This constant speed forms the basic building blocks of the physical universe, while at the same time indicating that everything in the universe has an interconnected and consistent order. In Islamic thought, this order in the universe is interpreted as an order reflecting the divine unity and power of Allah. The universality of the constant speed of light can be a symbol of a system in which all beings and events operate according to a divine will. The Quran also emphasizes that Allah has a power that encompasses everything and that the connection between beings is possible with his knowledge and power. The fact that light moves at an unchanging speed among all beings in the universe can be seen as a reflection of this divine order in the physical world. From the perspective of Sufism, light (nur) is considered a symbol of the unity and existence of Allah. The Surah an-Nur describes Allah as a being who illuminates, organizes and encompasses everything in the universe. In Islam, light is not only a physical phenomenon, but also the essence of divine knowledge and existence. The immutability of light can be associated with the immutability of divine will and knowledge in this sense. The fact that the speed of light is constant in the universe created by Allah can be interpreted as an indication of this divine order. Just as light always spreads at the same speed, the divine order is always consistent and unchanging. As a result, while the fact that light moves at a constant speed in the universe reflects a fundamental rule in the physical world, this situation can also be interpreted as a symbol of a divine order. In Islamic thought, Allah's power that encompasses and unites everything in the universe can have a similar meaning to the immutable speed of light. The constant speed of light carries a deep meaning both scientifically and metaphysically, as an expression of an order and consistency that is valid everywhere in the universe.\par
\par
\b 34- THE MYSTERY OF LIGHT DARK MATTER AND DARK ENERGY\b0\par
\par
Dark matter and dark energy are two of the greatest mysteries of the universe, and scientists have yet to fully explain these two phenomena. Dark matter is a type of matter that is thought to exist to explain the gravitational effects in the universe, but cannot be observed directly. Dark energy, on the other hand, is a mysterious type of energy that causes the universe to expand at an accelerating rate. The question of whether these two concepts represent unknown aspects of light can be addressed from both a scientific and philosophical perspective.\par
In a physical sense, dark matter and dark energy cannot be directly associated with light because they do not interact with electromagnetic waves, i.e. light. Dark matter affects the gravity around galaxies and other celestial bodies, but does not emit, absorb or reflect light. That is why it is called "dark". When it was insufficient to explain the distribution of observable matter, the concept of dark matter emerged. In other words, it does not represent unknown aspects of light, but an unseen and ununderstood form of matter.\par
Dark energy, on the other hand, is a type of energy that accelerates the expansion of the universe, further widening the gaps between galaxies. This phenomenon has revealed that the universe continues to expand rapidly and that this expansion is much faster than expected. Again, dark energy, although not directly related to light, symbolizes a form of energy that controls the expansion process in the universe and is difficult to understand. Instead of the unknown aspects of light, it can be interpreted as the power behind the expansion of the universe. However, beyond these scientific facts, from a metaphysical and philosophical perspective, dark matter and dark energy can represent the shadowy aspects of the symbolic meanings of light. Light is usually associated with knowledge, consciousness and enlightenment. In contrast, dark matter and dark energy may symbolize the parts of the universe that are not yet understood, with their mysterious and unknown dimensions. In Sufism, light (nur) is the symbol of divine knowledge and existence; darkness, on the other hand, has a meaning that is unknown, hidden or waiting to be revealed. In this respect, dark matter and dark energy can be considered metaphorical representatives of the unknown or yet to be discovered aspects of the universe. \par
Another interesting point is that light does not affect dark matter and dark energy. This shows that we are not limited to the observable light and matter in the universe, and that the unseen aspects of existence make up a much larger part of the universe. These unknowns point to deeper, mysterious dimensions of existence. As a result, dark matter and dark energy do not directly represent the unknown aspects of light, but they do express the mysterious, unexplored parts of the universe. From both a scientific and metaphysical perspective, dark matter and dark energy can be considered as the unknown aspects of the universe that remain in the dark, indicating that there is a greater reality waiting to be discovered beyond the areas illuminated by light.\par
