\b 40- THE PARTICLE-WAVE DUALITY OF LIGHT IN QUANTUM PHYSICS SHEDS LIGHT ON THE UNDERSTANDING OF EXISTENCE-NOTICE IN SUFISM\b0\par
\par
The fact that light exhibits both particle and wave properties in quantum physics sheds a deep metaphorical light on the understanding of \ldblquote existence and non-existence\rdblquote  in Sufism. These two concepts, which seem to be opposites but can exist at the same time, offer us an important perspective in understanding the paradoxes and deep truths that lie at the core of both the quantum world and Sufism.\par
In physics, the fact that light behaves both like a particle (photon) and a wave is a phenomenon known as \ldblquote wave-particle duality\rdblquote . Sometimes light behaves like a certain energy packet occupying a space, and sometimes like a wave spreading through space. This situation has puzzled scientists for a long time, because they have sought an answer to the question of how light can be both at a certain point (particle) and everywhere (wave) at the same time. Modern quantum physics has shown that this duality is related to the observer, meaning that light exhibits different behaviors depending on how it is measured. In Sufism, \ldblquote existence\rdblquote  (wujud) and \ldblquote non-existence\rdblquote  (adam) are deep metaphysical concepts that explain the creation of the universe in relation to the existence of Allah. While existence points to the absolute existence of Allah, the created world is considered a reflection of this existence. Non-existence, on the other hand, expresses that the created things cannot have an independent reality outside of their true nature and ultimately the existence of Allah. In other words, the world of existence is temporary and dependent on the divine existence, while non-existence is an aspect of the infinite reality behind this existence. In Sufism, this duality is resolved by the doctrine of \ldblquote Tawhid\rdblquote , or unity. Although existence and non-existence appear to be opposites in appearance, this opposition actually serves to comprehend the absolute unity of God and that everything is by His will. Non-existence expresses that existence does not merge into non-existence, on the contrary, everything that exists is in reality a manifestation of God.\par
The relationship between the simultaneous existence of light as a wave and particle in quantum physics and existence and non-existence in Sufism offers striking parallels in understanding the unity behind duality. Let's focus on the expression of Duality in Appearance, Unity in Reality. Light is sometimes observed as a wave and sometimes as a particle depending on an observer. Although existence and non-existence seem like two opposite poles in Sufism, they are actually a whole. While the existence of God underlies everything, non-existence expresses that what exists is not independent of Him. In other words, just as waves and particles are interdependent in quantum physics, existence and non-existence in Sufism are different aspects of the same reality.\par
In quantum mechanics, the behavior of light changes according to the observer's perspective. This shows that instead of an absolute reality, there is a relative reality. In Sufism, the absolute truth of existence is Allah. When a person looks at the world as an observer, they perceive material beings as real, but with a deep understanding, it becomes clear that these are only a reflection, an \ldblquote apparent reality\rdblquote . The real truth is the eternal and everlasting existence of Allah. Where exactly a particle of light is or when the wave will collapse is explained by quantum uncertainty. In Sufism, the fine line between existence and non-existence is a secret that a person cannot understand in an absolute sense, but can only grasp with spiritual perception. This uncertainty emphasizes that everything in the realm of existence depends on the will of Allah and that the human mind cannot fully solve this. \par
Light manifests itself as either a wave or a particle, depending on the observer\rquote s situation. In Sufism, created existence is a manifestation of the existence of Allah. However, this existence is not an absolute existence, it is a state of existence within non-existence. Allah is the only power that continues to create at every moment and can destroy everything at any time He wishes. This situation can be spiritually associated with the \ldblquote collapse of the wave function\rdblquote  in the quantum. Just as light takes shape through the effect of an observer, existence also emerges or disappears by the will of Allah. The particle and wave duality of light in quantum physics sheds important light on the understanding of existence and non-existence in Sufism. Both systems are aimed at understanding the unity that lies behind opposites. Just as light can be both a wave and a particle, existence and non-existence, although seemingly opposite to each other, are actually parts of a whole. The absolute existence of Allah is the infinite truth behind everything, and the realm of existence is a temporary reflection of this absolute reality. Like light, everything comes into being or disappears depending on the will of Allah, and this process offers a profound metaphor that combines the secrets of the quantum world with spiritual truths.\par
