The first light that emerged at the moment of the Big Bang carries a deep symbolism that reflects the divine will in the creation of the universe. This light represents both the formation of the universe in a physical sense and symbolizes the divine plan and will of creation in a spiritual sense. This perspective offers important inferences from both a cosmological and mystical perspective. The Big Bang represents the beginning of the universe and the emergence of time and space. The "first light," or cosmic microwave background radiation, that formed immediately after this event symbolizes the evolution of the universe from its initial state of hot and dense matter to its current state of cooling and expansion. The existence of this first light also suggests that creation took place within the framework of a divine plan.\par
The first light can be seen as a manifestation of the divine will at the beginning of creation. Sufi philosophy accepts that the will of God is the most fundamental power behind everything. From this perspective, the creation of the universe occurs as a result of a divine command. With the command "Be" (kun), the world of being and therefore the first light emerges. Light represents divine knowledge, wisdom and illumination in many religions and philosophies. In Sufism, the concept of "light" is accepted as a sign of the existence and manifestation of God. The first light is a reflection of the soul and divine wisdom of the universe. This light can be considered as a symbol of the divine knowledge and wisdom inherent in the essence of creation. The fact that the first light at the moment of the Big Bang created a cosmological existence also leads to deep thoughts on the nature of consciousness and existence. This light is a starting point that will affect all beings of the universe. The first light spreads from a single source and ensures the expansion of the universe. In Sufism, this situation can be associated with the understanding of "Unity of Being"; that is, the existence of Allah, the only being behind beings. The multiplicity of the universe is actually His manifestation. In this context, the first light is a reflection of the unity and multiplicity in the creation of the divine will. The first light also symbolizes the beginning of time and space. This reinforces the role of the divine will in the process of creation. The existence of time and space is necessary for the continuity and evolution of the realm of being. This shows that the divine will plays a regulatory role.\par
